"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45011","Department for Education","false","2014-03-31","<p>The Department for Education has not issued guidance to local authorities on how best to make use of unutilised foster carers. Local authorities are required, under Section 22G of the Children Act 1989, to take steps that secure, so far as reasonably practicable, sufficient accommodation within the authority's area that meets the needs of children that the local authority is looking after, and whose circumstances are such that it would be consistent with their welfare for them to be provided with accommodation that is in the local authority's area (‘the sufficiency duty').</p><p>Since April 2013 the Department has been working with consortia of local authorities and sector partners to:</p><ol><li>develop and test innovative solutions for the recruitment and retention of foster carers</li><li>identify gaps in the capacity of the foster carer workforce</li><li>develop effective strategies for recruiting and retaining foster carers.</li></ol><p>We will be sharing the lessons learned and disseminating any tools that have been developed during the project more widely following testing.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45011/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45011/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45011/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department issues guidance to local authorities on how best to make use of unutilized foster carers.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","193526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45012","Department for Education","false","2014-04-01","<p>The government's aim is to ensure that young people are equipped with the skills, experience and qualifications that employers want. The introduction of 16-19 study programmes will expand the provision of genuine work experience and work-related learning for all post-16 students. We have invested in new apprenticeships that are more employer-led than ever before, and introduced traineeships to give young people the skills and experience they need to compete successfully for a job. From September 2014, the Tech Level qualifications will provide a high-quality vocational alternative to A levels, leading to a recognised occupation.</p><p>These and other reforms arising from Professor Alison Wolf's 2011 review of vocational education have led to far-reaching improvements in vocational education. These include employer recognition of qualifications and simplified and better-funded arrangements for work experience.</p><p>Our reforms to GCSEs and A levels will secure rigorous, challenging qualifications which are responsive to the needs of students and employers. New GCSEs in English and mathematics, which will provide greater assurance of literacy and numeracy, will be taught from September 2015, with the first examinations in summer 2017.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45012/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45012/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45012/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to increase links between education and employment.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","193671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45013","Department for Education","false","2014-03-31","<p>The available evidence suggests that teachers adapt quickly to using tablets as a tool for learning.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45013/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45013/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45013/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the current level of teachers teaching ability whilst using tablet computers in primary schools.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","193624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45014","Department for Education","false","2014-03-31","<p>The guidance from the Health and Safety Executive is that, if asbestos is undamaged and unlikely to be disturbed, then it is usually safer to leave it in place and to manage it as required by the Control of Asbestos Regulations 2012. If asbestos is found to be in an unsealed, damaged or poor condition, then it should be repaired, sealed, enclosed or removed using trained personnel. The Department for Education has no plans to issue school-specific guidance.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45014/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45014/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45014/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will issue to schools specific guidance on removing asbestos from premises.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","193714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45015","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-03-27","<p>The Smart Meter Central Delivery Body intend to publish an updated Consumer Engagement Plan before the end of the year, where they will set out their plans for assisting microbusinesses.</p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45015/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-27T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45015/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45015/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when he expects the smart meter central delivery body to set out plans for assiting microbusinesses to use smart meters.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","193679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45016","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-01","<p>Safety and security are top priorities for the Government and there is a robust security framework in place for the civil nuclear industry. We seek continuous improvement in line with internationally established principles. The UK has a strong and effective independent regulator, the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR), which ensures compliance with the requirements placed on duty holders by the Nuclear Industries Security Regulations 2003 (as amended) and the performance-based National Objectives, Requirements and Model Standards (NORMS). There is extensive engagement between the Government, ONR and duty holders. The full set of UK commitments made at the Nuclear Security Summit which go towards meeting paragraph 27 of the Summit's Communiquécan be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nss2014.com/sites/default/files/documents/140321_uk_national_statement_on_commitments.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.nss2014.com/sites/default/files/documents/140321_uk_national_statement_on_commitments.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45016/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45016/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45016/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps the Government plans to take to deliver the commitments on nuclear security contained in paragraph 27 of the Hague Nuclear Security Summit Communiqué held in the Hague on 24 and 25 March 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","193687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45017","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-01","<p>The Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) has published strategies for the management of spent Magnox and Oxide fuel; it is from these spent fuels that plutonium is separated. These strategies are aligned with UK Government policy and their implementation is expected to see cessation of reprocessing in Magnox and THORP facilities during this decade.</p><p> </p><p>With respect to Magnox fuel, the intent is to reprocess all of it. Only a finite amount of Magnox fuel remains, which limits the amount of further separated plutonium that could be produced from reprocessing. Reprocessing is the only approved process for managing this metal fuel.</p><p> </p><p>With respect to Oxide Fuel management, an NDA paper sets out the strategy which is to complete the reprocessing contracts in THORP, as far as is reasonably practicable, and place the remaining fuel and any future arisings into interim storage pending disposal. The paper can be found at <a title="http://www.nda.gov.uk/documents/upload/Oxide-Fuels-Preferred-Options-June-2012.pdf" href="http://www.nda.gov.uk/documents/upload/Oxide-Fuels-Preferred-Options-June-2012.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.nda.gov.uk/documents/upload/Oxide-Fuels-Preferred-Options-June-2012.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Both these strategies see the amount of plutonium separated in the future being limited in line with national requirements.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45017/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45017/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45017/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps the Government plans to take to deliver the commitments on nuclear security contained in paragraph 21 of the Hague Nuclear Security Summit Communiqué of the Nuclear Security Summit held in the Hague on 24 and 25 March 2014 to keep the national stockpile of separated plutonium to the minimum level.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","193688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45020","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-03-31","<p>DECC does not hold any sub-national data on switching energy suppliers, data is only available for Great Britain. This data is published in table 2.7.1 of the DECC publication Quarterly Energy Prices, which is made available online at the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/quarterly-domestic-energy-switching-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/quarterly-domestic-energy-switching-statistics</a></p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45020/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45020/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45020/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have switched energy suppliers in (a) Brigg and Goole constituency, (b) Yorkshire and Humber and (c) England in each of the last 60 months.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","193622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45021","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-02","<p>The construction and use of oil and gas wells in the UK is subject to stringent regulation by the HSE to ensure the integrity of the well in all phases of its life. Recognised industry design and construction processes must be followed, and the operator's work and plans are subject to scrutiny by an independent well examiner as well as the HSE. Monitoring and inspections are be carried out by the Environment Agency, the HSE and the independent well examiner as appropriate. Oil and gas wells which have no further usefulness are plugged and capped to ensure the retention of any fluids in the well.</p><p> </p><p>We seek to improve this robust regulatory system further wherever practicable. Further consideration is being given to control and monitoring of methane emissions in the light of the recommendations of the report by Prof David Mackay and Dr Tim Stone on potential greenhouse gas emissions associated with shale gas production and use, published in September 2013.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45021/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-02T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45021/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45021/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps he plans to take to prevent leaks and improve monitoring at existing (a) in use and (b) extinct or abandoned onshore oil and gas sites.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","193663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45022","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-01","<p>The Department does not at present provide bilateral funding to Argentina.</p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45022/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45022/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45022/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what (a) direct and (b) indirect bilateral funding arrangements his Department has with governmental or non-governmental projects and bodies in Argentina.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","193646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45023","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-04-02","<p>A recently published paper by the ReFINE research consortium estimates that there are between fifty and a hundred historic wells in the UK for which no responsible person can be identified.</p><p> </p><p>Oil and gas wells in the UK which have no further usefulness are treated to ensure the retention of any fluids within the well. The bore is sealed with concrete plugs, while the well head it cut off below ground level and a steel cap welded to the top. The abandonment operations are subject to scrutiny by the HSE and the independent well examiner, and must comply with relevant industry standards. The site will then be restored to the appropriate standard prescribed by planning conditions.</p><p> </p><p>Wells are not monitored after the completion of the abandonment and site restoration operations. The ReFINE paper confirms that there are no pollution issues associated with historic oil and gas wells in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45023/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-02T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45023/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45023/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many old oil and gas wells there are in the UK for which no firm or company is responsible; and how such wells are monitored for leaks.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","193643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45024","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-03-31","<p>The first annual report on consumer-funded levies will be published to a timetable consistent with Ofgem's reporting on the Renewables Obligation for 2013/14, scheduled for March 2015. Officials are currently considering how that date could be brought forward.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45024/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45024/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45024/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the contribution of the Minister of State of 3 March 2014, Official Report, column 725, on Government levies on energy bills, when he plans to present to the House the first annual report on consumer-funded policies, covering actual expenditure and forecast expenditure.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","193691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45025","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-03-31","<p>The levy control framework has been designed with the flexibility to be able to respond to policy changes. The government expects to meet its renewable energy ambition as set out in the Electricity Market Reform Delivery Plan within the Levy Control Framework.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45025/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45025/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45025/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the contribution of the Minister of State of 3 March 2014, Official Report, column 721, on Government levies on energy bills, what assessment he has made of the potential effects of a freeze of the carbon floor price on the number and capacity of projects that will be brought forward under the levy control framework.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","193690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45026","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-03-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to answer given by my rt. hon. Friend the Minister of State for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General on 26 March 2014, <em>Official Report, Column 300W</em>.</p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45026/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-27T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45026/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45026/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what his Department's policy is on allowing officials to appear before all-party parliamentary groups.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","193555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45027","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-03-31","<p>Since the last annual report Martin Stewart has joined the Department as lead non-executive director on 3<sup>rd</sup> June 2013; and Tom Kelly joined on 3<sup>rd</sup> February 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Martin Stewart is CEO of Eurotaxglass Ltd. He is also a Non-Executive Director and Chair of the Audit Committee on London 2017 Ltd, and Non-Executive Director and Chair of the Audit Committee of SIS Ltd.</p><p> </p><p>Tom Kelly is currently the corporate communications director at Network Rail. He moves to become Strategic Communications Adviser for HS2 on 1<sup>st</sup> April 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Their fees are £20,000 PA and £15,000 PA respectively. Neither has claimed expenses from the Department since taking up their role.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45027/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45027/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45027/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, who has been appointed as a non-executive director of his Department since the publication of information on non-executive directors in his Department's Annual Report and Accounts 2012-13; what the date of each such appointment was; what annual fee is payable to each such person; what expenses and allowances each such person has claimed to date; and what other interests or employment each such person has.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","193606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45028","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-01","<p> </p><p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my Rt. Hon. friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General, Mr Francis Maude, on 26 March 2014, Official Report, Column 300W.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45028/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45028/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45028/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what his Department's policy is on allowing officials to appear before all-party parliamentary groups.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","193556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45030","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-01","<p> </p><p>The number of bovine TB reactors in the Republic of Ireland fell by over 65% between 1999 and 2013, from 44,903 to 15,612. This represents the lowest level since the eradication programme started in the 1950s. The Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine's wildlife policy statement of April 2013 concludes that it is satisfied that the culling of infected badgers, which is underpinned by research studies and sound science, has led to a significant reduction in the incidence of TB in cattle over the past decade.</p><p><a href="http://www.agriculture.gov.ie/animalhealthwelfare/diseasecontrol/bovinetbbrucellosiseradicationschemes/wildlifepolicybadgers/" target="_blank">http://www.agriculture.gov.ie/animalhealthwelfare/diseasecontrol/bovinetbbrucellosiseradicationschemes/wildlifepolicybadgers/ </a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45030/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45030/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45030/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what evidence his Department has collected on the effect of badger culls conducted in Ireland on levels of bovine TB in that country.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","193609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45034","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-04-01","<p> </p><p>Non-native wildlife specimens (including plants) may be retained for various reasons by the Police, UK Border Force (UKBF), Royal Botanic Gardens Kew (RBG Kew), local authorities and other organisations such as the RSPCA.</p><p>RBG Kew has a Plant Quarantine Unit and keeps records of all plant material entering its collections but not records of confiscated specimens that are returned to the people or location they were confiscated from.</p><p> </p><p>UKBF re-homes seized wildlife after having consulted with the Joint Nature Conservation Committee, the UK's CITES scientific authority for fauna, on appropriate location. It has not been UK practice to return wildlife to countries of export as there is no guarantee of its return to the wild or that it will not re-enter illegal trade. UKBF does not disclose publically the locations where seized items are held. All seized animals remain the property of the crown.</p><p>No police-run facilities exist for the retention and care of non-native wildlife species confiscated in the UK: each case is dealt with on an ad-hoc basis. Information about returned specimens is not held centrally.</p><p>Defra does not hold information about holding facilities used by local authorities and other organisations.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45034/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45034/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45034/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what facilities exist for the retention and care of non-native wildlife species confiscated in the UK; where those facilities are located; and how many times such non-native wildlife species confiscated have been returned to the people or location where they were first confiscated.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","193703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45053","Cabinet Office","false","2014-03-31","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45053/answer","PQ 193620.pdf","PQ 193620.pdf","Cancer Deaths - ONS Letter","Cancer Deaths - ONS Letter",,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45053/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45053/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the mortality rate from cancer has been in (a) Brigg and Goole constituency, (b) Yorkshire and Humber and (c) England in the last 15 years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","193620"
