"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45103","Home Office","false","2014-04-28","<p> </p><p>No unaccompanied child under the age of 18 can be forcibly removed from the UK <br>unless adequate care and reception arrangements are in place in their country <br>of origin. The difficulty of setting up suitable reception arrangements has <br>meant that, with the exception of transfers to other European Union countries <br>under the *Dublin Regulations, the Home Office does not routinely enforce the <br>return of unaccompanied children to any country. The majority of unaccompanied <br>children whose asylum claims are rejected are granted temporary leave which is <br>reviewed when they reach 17½ years of age. We believe that the vast majority of <br>enforced returns of unaccompanied children undertaken between 2006 and 2010 <br>were transfers under the Dublin Regulations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1:</strong><strong> Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children removals 2009 to 2013</strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Date of Removal</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>31</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Grand Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>53</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>‘Migrant children' have been interpreted as unaccompanied asylum seeking <br>children (UASC) in answering this question.<br><br>* The Dublin Regulation EC No. 343/2003 is a binding measure of European <br>Community law to determine which State should be responsible for examining an <br>application for asylum made within the EU territory.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45103/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-28T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45103/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45103/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45103/answer/previousversion/3800","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many unaccompanied migrant children have been forcibly removed to another country in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sarah Teather","Brent Central","Sarah Teather","193591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45104","Home Office","false","2014-03-31","<p>Data specific to your request can be found in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>Band Cases</p><p> </p><p>Up to two years 2008</p><p>More than two years 822</p><p>More than four years 473</p><p>More than six years 212</p><p> </p><p>Total 3515</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45104/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45104/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45104/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum applicants receiving support under section 4 of the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999 have been receiving support for more than (a) two years, (b) four years and (c) six years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sarah Teather","Brent Central","Sarah Teather","193593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45105","Home Office","false","2014-03-31","<p> </p><p>There are no immediate plans to change the support rates provided to destitute asylum seekers.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45105/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45105/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45105/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she will announce the asylum support rates for 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sarah Teather","Brent Central","Sarah Teather","193594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45109","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-04-01","<p>Information on the numbers of forced marriage protection orders that have been granted in England and Wales with a power of arrest attached, for each year since such orders came into force, are available in table 2.8 of the Court Statistics Quarterly bulletin. The latest edition of this publication is available at this link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/court-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/court-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2013</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45109/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45109/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45109/answer","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45109/answer/previousversion/3878","Biography information for Damian Green","54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many forced marriage protection orders have been granted with a power of arrest attached in each year since such orders came into force.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","193701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45110","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-03-31","<p>Figures provided in the statistical publication released on the 2nd January 2014 are available at <a title="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/legal-aid-statistics-barrister-fee-income-from-public-sources-201213" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/legal-aid-statistics-barrister-fee-income-from-public-sources-201213" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/legal-aid-statistics-barrister-fee-income-from-public-sources-201213</a> and show that when including all 4,931 criminal barristers' payments, the mean average payment for 2012/13 was £72,010. This includes those barristers that may have provided legal assistance in only a small number of instances within this time period, and payments from both the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) and Legal Aid Agency (LAA). The release also contains information on the data and methodology used.</p><p> </p><p>The statistics provided in the publication and supporting documents included VAT and other additional costs due to the structure of the data obtained from the administrative systems within LAA, and also those provided by the CPS were aggregated figures that already included VAT. The basis of the calculations were set out in the publication.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45110/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45110/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45110/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what calculations were used to calculate the mean fee income for full-time criminal barristers published by his Department on 2 January 2014; and for what reasons VAT was included in the estimate of barristers' earnings.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","193702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45111","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-03-31","<p> </p><p>I refer the hon Member to the answer given by the Minister for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General, my right hon. Friend the Member for Horsham on 26 March (<em>Official Report </em>col. 300W).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Simon Hughes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45111/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-31T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45111/answer","Biography information for Simon Hughes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45111/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his Department's policy is on allowing officials to appear before all-party parliamentary groups.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","193562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45112","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-04-03","<p> </p><p> </p><p>HM Prison The Verne started taking immigration detainees as scheduled from 24 March 2014. The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) will retain The Verne as a prison in the short term but its population will comprise immigration detainees as planned with the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>NOMS intends to review the designation of The Verne later this year, with the intention of completing the re-designation to an immigration removal centre by the end of September 2014.</p><p> </p><p>All foreign national offenders (FNOs) sentenced to custody are referred to the Home Office for them to consider deportation at the earliest possible opportunity.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice and the Home Office are committed to working together to expedite the removal of foreign criminals. NOMS will always supply sufficient prison places for those committed by the courts.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45112/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-03T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45112/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45112/answer","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45112/answer/previousversion/3879","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his plans are for HMP The Verne.","false","Biography information for Sarah Teather","Brent Central","Sarah Teather","193595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45113","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-04-03","<p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Up to 12 books may be held by prisoners in their cell at any one time. Prisoners may have additional books stored locally at the prison. Every prison has a library, to which every prisoner has access. </em></p><p> </p><p><em>Access to books is not determined by category of prisoner and nor does it differ for those in the first four weeks of their sentence.</em></p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45113/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-03T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45113/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45113/answer","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45113/answer/previousversion/3863","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what restrictions, by category of prisoner, are placed on access to (a) a prisoner's own books and (b) books from the prison library in the first four weeks of a prison sentence.","false","Biography information for Lord Blunkett","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Mr David Blunkett","193597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45114","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-04-01","<p>Our laws in these areas are robust and clear. The Government takes very seriously all matters relating to the sexual abuse of children. Those who commit sexual offences are more likely to go to prison now than in 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The number of defendants convicted of offences under section 1 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 where the victim was a child under 16, together with all offences under sections 2, 5, 6 and 7 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 can be viewed in the table. As the Sexual Offences Act 2003 replaced the Sexual Offences Act 1956 for these offences all proceedings reflect that Act too, as per the footnote.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics in respect of victims of offences under section 2 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 cannot be broken down by age.</p><p> </p><p>Also, my department's Court Proceedings Database holds information on criminal justice statistics only in England and Wales. Criminal Justice Statistics in Northern Ireland are a matter for the Department of Justice in Northern Ireland. Likewise, Criminal Justice Statistics in Scotland are a matter for the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45114/answer","193577, 193578, 193579, 193582.XLS","193577, 193578, 193579, 193582.XLS","Table 1","Table 1",,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45114/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45114/answer","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45114/answer/previousversion/3865","Biography information for Damian Green","54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been convicted of an offence contrary to section (a) 1, where the victim was a child, and (b) 5 of the Sexual Offences Act 1956 in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","193577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45115","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-04-01","<p>Our laws in these areas are robust and clear. The Government takes very seriously all matters relating to the sexual abuse of children. Those who commit sexual offences are more likely to go to prison now than in 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The number of defendants convicted of offences under section 1 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 where the victim was a child under 16, together with all offences under sections 2, 5, 6 and 7 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 can be viewed in the table. As the Sexual Offences Act 2003 replaced the Sexual Offences Act 1956 for these offences all proceedings reflect that Act too, as per the footnote.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics in respect of victims of offences under section 2 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 cannot be broken down by age.</p><p> </p><p>Also, my department's Court Proceedings Database holds information on criminal justice statistics only in England and Wales. Criminal Justice Statistics in Northern Ireland are a matter for the Department of Justice in Northern Ireland. Likewise, Criminal Justice Statistics in Scotland are a matter for the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45115/answer","193577, 193578, 193579, 193582.XLS","193577, 193578, 193579, 193582.XLS","Table 1","Table 1",,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45115/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45115/answer","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45115/answer/previousversion/3866","Biography information for Damian Green","54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been convicted of an offence contrary to articles (a) 5 and 6, where the victim was a child, and (b) 12, 13 and 14 of the Sexual Offences (Northern Ireland) Order 2008 in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","193578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45116","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-04-01","<p>Our laws in these areas are robust and clear. The Government takes very seriously all matters relating to the sexual abuse of children. Those who commit sexual offences are more likely to go to prison now than in 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The number of defendants convicted of offences under section 1 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 where the victim was a child under 16, together with all offences under sections 2, 5, 6 and 7 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 can be viewed in the table. As the Sexual Offences Act 2003 replaced the Sexual Offences Act 1956 for these offences all proceedings reflect that Act too, as per the footnote.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics in respect of victims of offences under section 2 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 cannot be broken down by age.</p><p> </p><p>Also, my department's Court Proceedings Database holds information on criminal justice statistics only in England and Wales. Criminal Justice Statistics in Northern Ireland are a matter for the Department of Justice in Northern Ireland. Likewise, Criminal Justice Statistics in Scotland are a matter for the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45116/answer","193577, 193578, 193579, 193582.XLS","193577, 193578, 193579, 193582.XLS","Table 1","Table 1",,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45116/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45116/answer","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45116/answer/previousversion/3868","Biography information for Damian Green","54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been convicted of an offence contrary to sections (a) 1 and 2, where the victim was a child, and (b) 18, 19 and 20(1), (2)(a) and (3) of the Sexual Offences (Scotland) Act 2009 in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","193579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45117","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-04-01","<p>Our laws in these areas are robust and clear. The Government takes very seriously all matters relating to the sexual abuse of children. Those who commit sexual offences are more likely to go to prison now than in 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The number of defendants convicted of offences under section 1 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 where the victim was a child under 16, together with all offences under sections 2, 5, 6 and 7 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 can be viewed in the table. As the Sexual Offences Act 2003 replaced the Sexual Offences Act 1956 for these offences all proceedings reflect that Act too, as per the footnote.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics in respect of victims of offences under section 2 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 cannot be broken down by age.</p><p> </p><p>Also, my department's Court Proceedings Database holds information on criminal justice statistics only in England and Wales. Criminal Justice Statistics in Northern Ireland are a matter for the Department of Justice in Northern Ireland. Likewise, Criminal Justice Statistics in Scotland are a matter for the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p>","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45117/answer","193577, 193578, 193579, 193582.XLS","193577, 193578, 193579, 193582.XLS","Table 1","Table 1",,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45117/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45117/answer","Ashford","Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45117/answer/previousversion/3876","Biography information for Damian Green","54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been convicted of an offence contrary to sections (a) 1 and 2 where the victim was a child, and (b) 5, 6 and 7 of the Sexual Offences Act 2003 in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","193582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45118","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-04-10","<p> </p><p> </p><p>Up to 12 books may be held by prisoners in their cell at any one time. Prisoners may have additional books stored locally at the prison. Every prison has a library, to which every prisoner has access.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers have not made any policy changes specifically about the availability of books in prisons. The changes to the Incentives and Earned Privileges national policy framework we introduced last year in relation to parcels were introduced to ensure consistency across the estate and to make sure that security can be maintained. There have always been controls on the sending of parcels into prisons, and allowing parcels to be sent in unrestricted would be operationally unmanageable and would lead to a significant risk of drugs and other illicit items being smuggled into prisons.</p><p> </p><p>The National Offender Management Service works closely with the Shannon Trust to support schemes such as 'Toe by Toe', which includes peer mentoring to improve reading levels.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45118/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-10T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45118/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45118/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reason the rules governing the provision of books to prisoners have recently been changed.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","193552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45119","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-04-01","<p> </p><p>I refer the hon Gentleman to the answer given by my Rt hon Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office and Paymaster General on 26 March, Official Report, Column 300W.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45119/answer",,,,,,"2014-04-01T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45119/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45119/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what her Department's policy is on allowing officials to appear before all-party parliamentary groups.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","193563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45120","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-03-27","<p> </p><p>I and officials in the NIO have remained in close contact with the US Administration on Northern Ireland matters such as the discussions to make progress on flags, parades and dealing with the past. </p><p>I have also discussed with representatives of the US Government the importance of rebalancing the economy and building a genuinely shared future for everyone in Northern Ireland. I am grateful for all their support for a better future for Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45120/answer",,,,,,"2014-03-27T12:00:00.00Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45120/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/45120/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-03-25","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions she has had with members of the US Administration on recent developments in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","193668"
